nt Society reveals the extent to which American collectivity has depended-and continues to depend-on the literary production of chance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChance in literature. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRealism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804778459zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804778459.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles